    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1824-08-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1824-08-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="130" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d130">
                <head>
                    <seg type="margin">[156]</seg>
                    <hi rend="italic">*Mr. <persName type="from">McCulloch</persName>,
                                    collector, to Mr. <persName type="to">Lowry</persName>,
                                    surveyor.</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Custom-House,
                                        Baltimore</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Collector’s
                                        Office</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1824-08-09">
                        <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 9,
                                1824</date>.</dateline>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Please to send two inspectors of the
                                customs to-morrow morning to examine the Colombian cruiser Aguila,
                                below the fort. The object is to ascertain that no addition is made
                                to her force by any new warlike equipments or enlistments of
                                American seamen. In case such should appear, you will direct the
                                officers to detain the commission, &amp;c., of the vessel herewith
                                sent and immediately report it here. If otherwise, they will deliver
                                the captain his papers, and if the cutter can be found, deliver
                                Captain Webster the letter handed herewith. Return if no occasion
                                requires a further proceeding. But if the cutter is not to be seen,
                                it will be proper for an officer to go on till she can be met with
                                or any other public vessel, to the commander of which the letter to
                                Captain Webster may then be delivered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J. H. McCULLOCH.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wm. Lowry</hi>, Esq.,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Surveyor of the Port of Baltimore.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
